==English==
===Etymology===
From the earlier form ''[[an't|an't]]'', a contraction of "are not" and "am not" [http://www.bartleby.com/61/63/A0156300.html]. Historically, it was present in many dialects of the English language except that of southeast England, which became the standard.

===Contraction===
'''ain't''' ''slang in all senses''

# [[are]] [[not]], [[aren't|aren't]].
# [[is]] not, [[isn't|isn't]].
# [[am]] not.
# [[have]] not, [[haven't|haven't]].
# [[has]] not, [[hasn't|hasn't]].

====Usage note====

*This word is still considered an [[illiteracy]] and can stigmatize the user as ignorant.  

===Quotations===

*'''1885''' — [[w:Gilbert and Sullivan|Gilbert & Sullivan]], ''[[s:The_Mikado|The Mikado]]''
*:We figure in lively paint -
*:Our attitude's queer and quaint —
*:You're wrong if you think it '''ain't''', oh!

